Title: A "Linear Logic" Quicksort  
Author: Henry G. Baker 
Address: 16231 Meadow Ridge Way, Encino, CA 91436  
Affiliation: Nimble Computer Corporation,  
Note: ACM Sigplan Notices 29,2 (Feb.1994), 13-18. Copyright 1993 by Nimble Computer Corporation 1  This material is based upon work supported by the National Science Foundation under Grant No. III-9261682.  
Abstract: The linear style of programming inspired by linear logic has been proposed to reduce garbage collection and synchronization costs in serial and parallel systems. We programmed Quicksort for both lists and arrays in a "linear" fragment of Lisp to estimate the performance impact of linearity on a serial machine. Even though Quicksort is well-tuned for current nonlinear architectures, we find that linearity extracts no real penalty. Our "linear" list Quicksort is as fast as any nonlinear list Quicksort, and our "linear" vector Quicksort is only 3.5% slower than a nonlinear vector Quicksort. The linear style is moderately pleasant, and the redundancy of linearity checking can aid in finding bugs. 
